## The problem: CUDA is NVIDIA-only

The upstream ALIEN requires an NVIDIA GPU with compute capability 6.0+.

I have an AMD RX 7900 XTX with 24 GB of VRAM. It speaks ROCm/HIP, not CUDA.

Automatic translation tools exist, such as [SCALE](https://scale-lang.com/) and [ZLUDA](https://github.com/vosen/ZLUDA).

The goal: port ALIEN source code to HIP and compile/run natively on AMD GPUs, with no runtime behaviour changes.

## CUDA vs HIP

HIP is AMD's portability layer. It mirrors the CUDA API almost exactly.

    CUDA                      HIP
    ------------------------  ------------------------
    cudaMalloc                hipMalloc
    cudaMemcpy                hipMemcpy
    __syncthreads()           __syncthreads()
    cudaDeviceSynchronize     hipDeviceSynchronize
    .cu / .cuh                .hip / .hip.h

The semantics are the same. The namespaces differ.

HIP compiles to either NVIDIA (`nvcc` backend) or AMD (`hipcc` via ROCm).
With `__HIP_PLATFORM_AMD__` defined, you target ROCm.

## hipify-perl

AMD ships `hipify-perl`, a Perl script that mechanically translates CUDA source to HIP.

    #!/usr/bin/env bash
    find source -type f \( -name "*.cu" -o -name "*.cuh" \) | while read -r file; do
        hipify-perl --inplace "$file"
        case "$file" in
            *.cu)  mv "$file" "${file%.cu}.hip"   ;;
            *.cuh) mv "$file" "${file%.cuh}.hip.h" ;;
        esac
    done

This handles the mechanical part: namespace prefixes, type names, function names.

After running it, ALIEN had `.hip` kernel files where there were `.cu` files.

## What hipify cannot do

hipify handles the easy cases. The hard cases are manual.

- **CUDA-OpenGL interop**: `cudaGraphicsGLRegisterImage`, `cudaGraphicsMapResources`, etc. — these are NVIDIA-only extension paths. AMD has its own `hipGraphicsGLRegisterImage` but the semantics and extension string differ.
- **Wavefront vs warp size**: NVIDIA warps are 32 threads. AMD wavefronts are 64 threads on GCN, 32 on RDNA. Block sizes tuned for 32 need adjustment.
- **Cooperative groups**: some CUDA cooperative group APIs have no direct HIP equivalent.
- **Device function qualifiers**: some `__device__` / `__host__` combinations behave differently under `hipcc`.

## CMake changes

The upstream CMakeLists used `LANGUAGES CUDA`. HIP needs its own language declaration:

    # Before
    project(alien-project LANGUAGES C CXX CUDA)

    # After
    project(alien-project LANGUAGES C CXX HIP)

And the compile definition that tells HIP which platform we target:

    add_compile_definitions(__HIP_PLATFORM_AMD__)

The build script sets up the ROCm environment and pins the architecture:

    cmake \
        -S . -B build \
        -DCMAKE_MODULE_PATH=/opt/rocm/lib/cmake/hip \
        -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release \
        -DCMAKE_HIP_ARCHITECTURES="gfx1100"

`gfx1100` is the shader model for the RX 7900 XTX (RDNA 3).

## OpenGL interop

CUDA-OpenGL interop lets kernels write directly into an OpenGL texture on the GPU without a round-trip through CPU memory.

The approach for AMD uses a different extension path:

    // CUDA path: cudaGraphicsGLRegisterImage
    cudaGraphicsResource* resource;
    cudaGraphicsGLRegisterImage(&resource, texId,
        GL_TEXTURE_2D, cudaGraphicsRegisterFlagsWriteDiscard);

    // HIP/AMD path: gl_sharing extension, then hipGraphicsGLRegisterImage
    // Requires EGL or GLX context with the AMD interop extension enabled
    hipGraphicsResource* resource;
    hipGraphicsGLRegisterImage(&resource, texId,
        GL_TEXTURE_2D, hipGraphicsRegisterFlagsWriteDiscard);

The AMD path needs the context to be created with `AMD_gpu_association` active.
Fallback: copy the render buffer from VRAM to system RAM, then upload as a texture — slower but it works everywhere.

## Tuning for RDNA 3

RDNA 3 wavefront size is 32 (same as NVIDIA warp). GCN was 64; some legacy AMD code assumes 64.

The kernel launch parameters were already tuned for 32-thread warps, so no changes needed there.

Block sizes for the physics kernels:

    // Physics update: one thread per particle cluster
    dim3 block(NUM_THREAD_BLOCKS, 1);
    dim3 grid(cudaBlockCount(numObjects, NUM_THREAD_BLOCKS), 1);

`NUM_THREAD_BLOCKS` defaults to 64, fine for both NVIDIA and RDNA 3.

Adjusting `--num-blocks` at runtime lets you tune for your specific GPU.

## Result

ALIEN compiles and runs on an RX 7900 XTX with ROCm (CMake 3.31, ROCm 7.2).

Benchmark on the default simulation with an RX 7900 XTX:

    500 time steps, 2934 ms → 170.4 TPS  (CLI)
    ~130 TPS, ~40 FPS @ 4K              (GUI)
    ~200 TPS                             (GUI, rendering disabled with ALT+I)

- 2.4× faster than the SCALE automatic-translation version (130 vs 53 TPS)
- OpenGL interop works via the AMD extension path
- Port targets the 4.x stable branch (September 2024)

